    Hointer: How a mathematician got micro-robots to sell you jeans






Sue Mitchell








facebook
SHARE




twitter
TWEET




email




google-plus




linkedin




reddit



More




Nadia Shouraboura’s mathematician parents were disappointed she pursued a career in retail rather than academia, but the former Amazon executive may hold the keys to success for bricks and mortar retailers in a digital age.“There’s a very beautiful part of retail, the beauty of the store and the fun that people have when they go to the store,” says Ms Shouraboura, founder and chief executive of retail technology firm Hointer. “But there is a part that’s really old and hasn’t changed much . . . it could be a great experience if they added great technology to it.”


SHARE



Share on Facebook
SHARE



Share on Twitter
TWEET



Link




    Hointer CEO Nadia Shouraboura. Photo: Lisa Maree Williams



The Soviet-born mathematician, software developer and robotics engineer believes bricks and mortar retailers are better placed than pure-play online retailers to satisfy consumer demand for products such as apparel and consumer electronics.However, many traditional retailers are stuck in the 20th century, burdened with inefficient systems and costs that make it almost impossible to compete with low-cost online rivals.“When I look at e-commerce in the past 15 years, the progress has been on the technology side, but when I look at retail I don’t see much progress at all,” Ms Shouraboura told Fairfax Media ahead of an online retail conference in Sydney this week.After almost nine years running ­supply chain, fulfilment and inventory buying at Amazon, Ms Shouraboura started developing a suite of retail ­technologies that promise to transform bricks and mortar retailers by giving them the tools to compete with online retailers while reducing rent, labour and inventory costs.
Advertisement




Two years ago she launched Hointer, a chain of menswear stores that acts as a test lab for innovation and a showroom for prospective retail partners.There is little stock on shelves and less than a handful of staff.



You will now receive updates from
Business AM Newsletter








Business AM Newsletter

Get the latest news and updates emailed straight to your inbox.







By submitting your email you are agreeing to Fairfax Media's
                
                    terms and conditions
                
                and
                
                    privacy policy
                
                .
            


Micro robots
Shoppers download the Hointer app, make their selection from about 150 styles of jeans, shirts and tops ­suspended on steel cables and scan a QR code with their smartphone or tablet. Within 30 seconds the products are despatched via micro-robotics from storeroom to designated dressing rooms. Unwanted items are discarded in a chute and deleted from shopping carts while wanted items are purchased by swiping a credit or debit card.Hointer stores have one-fifth the floor space of traditional stores, as inventory is tightly packed in storerooms rather than displayed on shelves, and half the number of staff, who have more time to serve customers. Costs are substantially lower, while the sales uplift is estimated to be between 30 per cent and 50 per cent. “Customers who come to Hointer end up trying on a lot more items,” Ms Shouraboura said. “Normally customers try on three to five – at Hointer on average they try on 12 because it’s very fast.”Ferrier Hodgson retail partner James Stewart says the technology and store experience pioneered by Hointer could be a game changer for retailers.“The tech companies think this is a really interesting concept and ultimately you could see a blend of this sort of technology with human interaction,” Mr Stewart said.“The role that retail staff will play in the next five years will be a lot less about the checkout process and a lot more about the value-add process.”Ms Shouraboura is now in talks with several retailers, including a major consumer electronics chain in the United States, about incorporating Hointer’s technology into their models.It may seem futuristic, but Ms Shouraboura believes some of Hointer’s retail technology will eventually become mainstream. “It works well for apparel, it works well for toys, it works well for electronics when customers want to experience before they decide, it works for jewellery and it will probably work well for grocery,” she said.





















